Week 8 Events\
\
Power and Authority\
\
1. President Donald Trump ordered transgender women in federal custody transferred to men's prisons despite court rulings (2025-03-08): The order overrode prior court blocks and placed transgender women in men's facilities, signaling willingness to defy judicial limits and exposing a vulnerable group to heightened risk from state power.\
\
2. President Donald Trump and Elon Musk expanded presidential authority and empowered the Department of Government Efficiency to slash the federal workforce and functions (2025-03-08): Centralizing sweeping downsizing power in a quasi-private unit undercuts normal agency chains of command and weakens checks on executive control over the civil service.\
\
3. President Donald Trump signed an executive order creating a taxpayer-backed US Crypto Reserve (2025-03-08): Using public funds to support a favored speculative industry while easing enforcement against it blurs lines between public policy and private gain and weakens impartial financial regulation.\
\
4. President Donald Trump pardoned individuals convicted for the January 6 Capitol attack (2025-03-08): Granting clemency to participants in an attack on the transfer of power undermined accountability for political violence and signaled tolerance for future anti-democratic force.\
\
5. Department of Homeland Security under Secretary Kristi Noem removed union protections from tens of thousands of TSA employees (2025-03-09): Stripping collective bargaining rights from frontline security staff weakened worker voice in a key security agency and increased executive leverage over a sensitive workforce.\
\
6. Department of Health and Human Services offered large buyouts to tens of thousands of employees during a measles outbreak (2025-03-09): Incentivizing rapid staff reductions amid an active epidemic risked degrading public health capacity when effective state response was most needed.\
\
7. Social Security Administration changed overpayment recovery rules to allow 100% benefit withholding (2025-03-09): Authorizing full benefit clawbacks from overpaid recipients, regardless of fault, increased executive leverage over vulnerable beneficiaries and risked pushing many into destitution.\
\
8. Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent announced an administration goal to shrink and privatize federal services (2025-03-09): Framing privatization as a core response to economic strain signaled a strategic shift of public functions into less accountable private hands.\
\
9. President Donald Trump publicly defended Elon Musk and labeled Tesla protesters as domestic terrorists (2025-03-12): Branding peaceful corporate critics as terrorists used presidential rhetoric to stigmatize dissent and protect an allied business figure.\
\
10. Office of Personnel Management under the Trump administration directed mass layoffs of probationary federal employees across agencies (2025-03-12): Coordinated purges of probationary staff allowed rapid reshaping of the civil service along political lines, weakening neutral administrative capacity.\
\
11. Environmental Protection Agency under Administrator Lee Zeldin announced reconsideration of the 2009 greenhouse gas endangerment finding (2025-03-13): Reopening the scientific basis for regulating greenhouse gases threatened to dismantle core climate protections and expand executive discretion over environmental risk.\
\
12. Environmental Protection Agency under Administrator Lee Zeldin announced a sweeping rollback of dozens of environmental regulations (2025-03-13): Revoking rules on vehicle emissions and coal pollution shifted regulatory power toward polluting industries and away from public health protections.\
\
13. House Republicans passed a measure redefining days to block congressional termination of Trump\'92s tariff emergency (2025-03-13): By manipulating statutory timing rules, lawmakers insulated an emergency declaration from normal review, entrenching executive control over trade policy.\
\
